anada, bringing to the fore the opinions and perceptions of a broad range of Canadians – from consumers to diplomats, jazz musicians to urban planners, and a diverse cross-section in between. As they grappled with issues including constitutional reform, transit policy, national security, the arrival of television, white supremacy, and postwar domesticity, Canadians were ever mindful of the unfolding American experience and its influence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aNational securityzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh1 aAzzi, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBryden, P.E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColbourn, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDorais, FranÇois-Olivier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEnglish, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFillion, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHillmer, Norman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeduc, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiverant, Bettina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKercher, Asa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKercher, Asa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPoitras, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSayle, Timothy Andrews, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStevenson, Michael D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStevenson, Michael D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabula